Morphology and anatomy.
Sponge massive, spherical to sub-spherical, covered by a smooth cortex. Apical osculum surrounded by membrane (
Fig 8A
). Hard and friable. There are subcortical inhalant cavities and the canals are disposed in parallel, giving a radial organisation to the choanosome. Large exhalant canals arrive into the atrium, giving it a reticulated appearance. Aquiferous system leuconoid. The skeleton is composed of giant triactines, present mainly on the cortex, and small triactines and tetractines (
Fig 8B
). The small triactines are present on the cortex and choanosome, while the small tetractines, which are few, are found only in the choanosome, mainly in the exhalant canals.

Tetractines
. Regular to subregular. They are very few. Actines are conical with sharp tips but some have cylindrical actines. The apical actine is conical, sharp, smooth and curve (
Fig 8G
). Size: 107.8/ 10.0 µm (basal actine); 32.0/ 
5.2 µm
(apical actine; 
Fig 8H
).
